The Compliance Model Governance Guide is one of the strongest sources for understanding the relationship among the Branch’s compliance systems. It identifies the core compliance models—Transaction Monitoring, Filtering Program, and Customer Risk Rating—and describes the broader model governance framework supporting these systems. The document references a range of supporting artifacts, including model and rule documentation, data mapping specifications, data dictionaries, data quality considerations, reconciliation processes, system calibration and tuning, validation activities, and change management practices. It also outlines the roles of Compliance, IT, Risk Management, Data Governance, and senior management in overseeing model performance and ensuring that changes are reviewed, tested, approved, implemented, and documented.

However, while these components are referenced, they are not fully integrated into a comprehensive, end-to-end data lineage and control framework that demonstrates complete traceability, validation, and alignment with DFS 504 data integrity requirements.
